{
  "summary": "Map the HLD generation system: prompt section structure, session-builder recipe, frontend conversation-JSON contract for hld mode, and which HLD topics already exist",
  "agentCount": 4,
  "logs": [],
  "result": {
    "prompt": {
      "sections": [
        {
          "title": "## 1. Requirements (Functional + Non-Functional)",
          "summary": "Open with the 🎬 structure pitch as a 🎙️ line + one line framing the core tension; list 3-5 core Functional flows 'above the line' (each with: the feature one-liner, '🗣️ Plain words', '⚡ Why it's hard') plus a 'Below the line (out of scope)' list; Non-Functional qualities each with talkable target (9s/p99), '🗣️ Plain words', '💥 What breaks without it'; optional '⚠️ Gaps I'd flag out loud'; close with a 🎙️ Script. TEXT ONLY, no tools."
        },
        {
          "title": "## 2. Clarifying Questions & Assumptions",
          "summary": "For each question, FOUR things: the question as a spoken sentence, '🗣️ Why I'm asking (plain words)', '↔️ Design fork' (If YES.../If NO...), and 'Assumption I'll proceed with'. TEXT ONLY (no tools yet); end with a 🤝 Checkpoint."
        },
        {
          "title": "## 3. Scale & Capacity (talkable numbers)",
          "summary": "First tool use allowed. Each number shown as a full visible arithmetic derivation chain in a table: Metric | Derivation (step-by-step math) | Rounded | Talkable phrase | Decision it drives. Gloss every term inline; name the ONE decision-forcing number + its flip threshold; treat storage/non-decision numbers as a half-sentence aside. End with a SHORT 🎙️ Script (2-4 sentences) speaking aloud only the 1-2 decision-driving rounded numbers + the constraint they force."
        },
        {
          "title": "## 4. Core Entities",
          "summary": "For each entity THREE things: 'Entity name' (what it is / what it owns), '🗣️ Simple analogy' (real-world comparison), '⚠️ The interviewer probe' (likely hard question + one-line answer). State this is a first draft with full fields in the data model. Close with a 🎙️ Script naming entities, flagging the most important one, and what the data model will add."
        },
        {
          "title": "## 5. API / Interface",
          "summary": "Go one-by-one through functional requirements (usually 1:1 endpoints). For each: Method + path (why this HTTP verb), 2-4 key request fields (fieldName: type + why; call out intentionally absent server-set fields), a concrete JSON request+response example with realistic values, and one key design decision (idempotency key, PENDING vs sync, redirect vs JSON). Default REST; security note (identify caller from session/JWT, never trust client ids/prices). 💬 note + 🎙️ Script walking the endpoints."
        },
        {
          "title": "## 6. High-Level Design (built one functional requirement at a time)",
          "summary": "One ### 6.x subsection per above-the-line requirement, in priority order, starting minimal. Each: one-sentence framing; ARCHITECTURE DECISIONS TABLE (Component | What it is plain English | Why THIS choice | What we DIDN'T pick & why not | Trade-off accepted, 2-5 rows) + a 🎙️ narration; a '🗣️ Key terms for this slice' GLOSSES BLOCK (one standalone bolded entry per term); a focused mermaid flowchart TD diagram (skip with a '↳ builds on §6.x' note if no new components); NUMBERED STEP NARRATION (action / why this component / state change / what could go wrong); a 💬 say-while-drawing line; a 🎙️ Script. Ends with the ONE 'Final (high-level)' diagram that is the exact reconciled union of all slices + 🎙️ Script + 🤝 Checkpoint."
        },
        {
          "title": "## 7. Data Model & Storage",
          "summary": "PART A entity table (Entity | Key fields with PK/shard key annotated | Chosen store | Shard/partition key | Consistency guarantee); PART B a standalone storage decision card per distinct store (What it is plain words / Why we picked it - the access pattern that forces it / What we considered & rejected with concrete reasons / Trade-off accepted / 🗣️ How to say it out loud); PART C per-operation consistency summary table (Operation | Store | Consistency level | Why right here, covering strong writes, eventual reads, read-your-own-writes). 🎙️ Script of 4-6 sentences with one 'considered X but rejected because Y'."
        },
        {
          "title": "## 8. Deep Dives — Bad → Good → Great (the senior signal)",
          "summary": "Where the interview is won. Open with a 🆘 'If you get stuck' pointer. Pick 3-5 hardest problems, each posed as '### How do we [problem]?'. Escalate through Bad/Good/Great tiers, each with fixed structure: (Good/Great) '↩️ What the previous tier got wrong', '🗣️ What this is in plain words', 'Approach' (mechanism, terms defined inline), 'Why people try this', '⚠️ What breaks (Challenges)' with concrete numbers, '🔁 What forces the upgrade'. Good/Great get a tier-specific mechanism diagram; Great adds '🔢 Decision-forcing math' and a '✅ Failure matrix'. Each deep dive ends with a 🎙️ Script + 🧠 'If they ask...'. Tiers optional. Covers bottleneck/relief/new ceiling, hot-key/celebrity, idempotency, global coordinators, consistency + read-your-own-writes, failure behavior."
        },
        {
          "title": "## 9. Reliability, Failure Modes & Cost",
          "summary": "Four named sub-sections with plain-English term definitions: 9A Availability targets (nines per path + human-terms downtime + mechanisms like multi-AZ); 9B per-dependency failure table (Component | What breaks | How it degrades gracefully (what the USER SEES) | Recovery action); 9C RPO/RTO per data class (define RPO/RTO in plain words first, then table Data class | RPO | RTO | Mechanism); 9D cost breakdown (top 3 cost drivers + why each is expensive + rough monthly order-of-magnitude + the one biggest optimization). 🎙️ Script of 3-4 sentences on what the user experiences when things fail."
        },
        {
          "title": "## 10. Trade-off Ledger",
          "summary": "For each of the 2-4 most significant decisions, a DECISION CARD '🔀 Decision: [chose] vs [didn't]' with five parts: What we chose and why / What we gave up / 🗣️ Plain words / When this reverses (exact flip condition) / 🗣️ How to say it. Tie back to non-functional requirements and any §1 '⚠️ Gaps'. 🎙️ Script of 3-4 sentences walking the ledger and what would change your mind."
        },
        {
          "title": "## 11. Likely Interviewer Questions & Answers",
          "summary": "Cover all 7 domains (core algorithm/hardest part, failure scenarios, scale/hot-spot, consistency/correctness, security, cost, extensibility), 2-3 per domain, 12-18 total. Each question: '❓ [question verbatim]', 'The mechanism (what actually happens)' 2-3 sentences with inline term definitions, '🗣️ In plain words' jargon-free fallback, '💬 One-liner to say out loud'. Answers must be real and specific with numbers. Ends with a 🎙️ '60-second verbal summary' in flowing connected sentences following the read/write-halves template."
        }
      ],
      "diagramsExpected": "Diagrams are MANDATORY and central, emitted as fenced ```mermaid blocks (render to SVG). Diagram kinds by purpose: flowchart TD (the DEFAULT for high-level design / layered architecture and multi-path flows — never flowchart LR for multi-path HLD because it stretches off a 13-inch screen; LR only for a dead-simple 3-4 node linear chain), sequenceDiagram (request/interaction flow), classDiagram (class structure, LLD), erDiagram (data models, though a Markdown table is preferred). WHERE: Section 6 is the diagram-heavy section — EVERY §6.x slice subsection gets its OWN focused diagram + numbered narration (skip only with an explicit '↳ builds on §6.x diagram — no new components' note when the slice adds no new components), and §6 ends with exactly ONE 'Final (high-level)' diagram that is the reconciled union of all slices (nothing dropped, nothing new). Section 8 deep dives: each meaningful tier (usually Good and Great) gets a titled mermaid diagram showing ONLY that tier's mechanism, not the whole system. So roughly one diagram per functional requirement (3-5) + one final union diagram + ~2 mechanism diagrams per deep dive across 3-5 deep dives. CONVENTIONS (strict): use the hourglass/diamond layout (single entry node at top with NO subgraph wrapper, two side-by-side subgraphs for parallel paths e.g. '⚡ Read path' vs '🔄 Async/Write path', shared storage nodes below outside subgraphs, cold/fallback at the very bottom); edges between entry node and subgraphs go OUTSIDE the subgraph defs to force side-by-side rendering. SAME ENTITY SAME EVERYWHERE — a component keeps the same node id, label, and color in every diagram. Semantic color palette defined once and reused: client=blue (#4A90D9 / #1a3a5c fill), svc/our services=green (#2E7D4F / #2ea043), async/queues=amber (#B7791F), store/datastores=grey (#4A5568 / #6B7280) drawn as cylinders [(name)], external=purple (#6B46C1 / #a78bfa); all fills dark enough for white text. Cap ~10-12 nodes per diagram (split if bigger). EVERY edge must have a SHORT label including a step number AND 2-4 word description (e.g. -->|\\\"3: read leaderboard\\\"|), numbered 1:1 with the prose steps; dashed -.-> for async/fire-and-forget. Use subgraph only when it genuinely clarifies. linkStyle to distinguish path types (green thick for sync/hot read, amber dashed for async, grey dashed for fallback/cache-miss, blue thick for entry). One bold caption line above each diagram, plus a one-line intro and a words explanation after. MERMAID SAFETY: keep labels free of breaking chars ( ) [ ] | : / \\\" < > and curly braces; use <br/> not raw newlines; in erDiagram write attributes as just 'type name' with no quoted comments or enum value lists.",
      "capacityEstimation": "Capacity/back-of-envelope estimation lives in Section 3 'Scale & Capacity (talkable numbers)' and is the FIRST place tool use is allowed (tools must NOT be called before the opener, Sections 1-2, are fully emitted as text). Arithmetic must be COMPUTED exactly by writing Python to a file (Write, with a relative path like capacity.py) and running it via Bash (python3 capacity.py) — never hand-waved, never shown unrun. Present each number as a table row with the FULL visible derivation chain so the candidate can explain HOW not just WHAT: format 'Metric | Derivation (step-by-step math) | Rounded | Talkable phrase | Decision it drives' — e.g. '1B users × 0.1% DAU = 1M DAU; 1M × 10 reads/day ÷ 86,400s ≈ 116/s → round to ~120/s'. Only compute the few numbers that actually influence the design (skip vanity 'it's a lot' math). EVERY number must be ROUNDED to a memorable, say-out-loud figure (~500K writes/s, ~100:1 read:write, ~$200K/mo, ~16K QPS) with NO false precision (never '15,625 QPS' or '$197,932/mo'). Feature the ONE number that forces a design choice and the exact threshold where that choice flips (e.g. 'a Redis node tops out ~150K ops/s, we're at 500K → shard'). Math written in PLAIN TEXT only (no LaTeX, no \\\\frac, no $...$): use '~', 'x' for multiply, '÷', '62^7 ≈ 3.5 trillion'. Specific rigor invariants govern it: size the read tier from MISS QPS not cache size (defended hit-ratio → residual DB QPS → replica/primary counts → cold-cache 0% worst case); storage = full footprint (per-row bytes + every index/secondary table + replication factor + WAL/compaction 3-6x headroom + the largest/events table + rough monthly $ naming the dominant driver, often egress/CDN or OLAP not the primary DB); decompose the p99 budget across DNS/TLS/CDN/LB/app/cache/DB hops so it sums to the SLO, separating cache-hit from cache-miss and cross-region paths. Treat storage and non-decision numbers as a half-sentence aside ('storage's a non-issue, a few TB'). End with a SHORT 🎙️ Script (2-4 sentences) speaking aloud ONLY the one or two decision-driving heavily-rounded numbers ('about 8 thousand reads a second') + the ratio/constraint they force + the conclusion ('so I'll spend my budget on reads, not writes').",
      "mustHaves": [
        "API design — Section 5: REST by default, method+path with HTTP-verb justification, 2-4 key request fields with why, intentionally-absent server-set fields called out, concrete JSON request+response examples with realistic values, one key design decision per endpoint, security (caller from session/JWT, never trust client ids/prices)",
        "Data model — Section 7: entity table with PK/shard key annotated + chosen store + partition key + consistency guarantee; storage decision card per store; per-operation consistency summary table",
        "Scaling strategy + capacity math — Section 3: computed (Python via Bash), full derivations, rounded talkable numbers, the one decision-driving number + its flip threshold",
        "Bottlenecks — name the ONE binding bottleneck under peak (including hot-key/celebrity single-shard QPS), quantify its ceiling, show the relief and the NEW ceiling (rigor invariant 8; surfaced in §8 deep dives)",
        "Trade-offs — Section 10 Trade-off Ledger: 2-4 decision cards (chose vs didn't / gave up / plain words / when it reverses / how to say it), tied back to non-functional reqs and §1 gaps",
        "Deep dives Bad→Good→Great — Section 8: 3-5 hardest problems, each escalated through tiers with mechanism diagrams, decision-forcing math, and a failure matrix for correctness-critical ones",
        "Idempotency on EVERY mutating endpoint (rigor invariant 7): idempotency/natural key + dedup store with TTL, what a retried request returns, no shared-namespace collisions",
        "Examine EVERY global coordinator (rigor invariant 9): counter/allocator/sequencer/lock/leader/quorum — its throughput ceiling, cold-start/partition behavior, what invariant breaks when down",
        "Consistency per operation and path, not one global label (rigor invariant 6): explicitly trace read-your-own-writes across cache miss, lagging replica, far region, cold edge; state staleness bound + mitigation",
        "Multi-region / async (rigor invariant 10): geo-routing + write topology (single-write-region vs multi-master), cross-region latency + replica-lag, delivery guarantee (at-most/at-least/exactly-once) tied to an accuracy SLA with idempotent consumer",
        "Reliability/DR/security/ops as first-class — Section 9 (rigor invariant 11): availability in 9s, per-dependency graceful degradation, RPO/RTO per data class with tested restore, multi-AZ vs multi-region failover triggers, deploy/rollback + reversible migrations, authn/authz + abuse defense + PII/retention/right-to-erasure, SLO burn-rate alerts + tracing + runbooks",
        "Cost — Section 9D and rigor: top 3 cost drivers with plain why, rough monthly order-of-magnitude, the one biggest optimization",
        "SLOs/objective as numbers up front (rigor invariant 4): target percentile, scope/region, window, and what you are NOT optimizing; revisit at the end",
        "🎙️ SAY-IT Scripts at the end of (nearly) every section — connected first-person read-aloud narration (~3-6 sentences) that alone form a complete spoken walkthrough",
