        "🤝 Checkpoints at exactly the three seams (after Requirements, after high-level design, before deep dives)",
        "🆘 Recovery lines block right before the deep dives (don't-know-a-tech / are-you-sure / you-blank)",
        "⚠️ Traps — problem-specific candidate-sinking mistakes (wrong move → why it sinks you → right move), woven where each bites",
        "🏢 Company x Level lens — state the company/level assumption in the opener and tilt the leading deep dive, the featured number, and vocabulary (here: Amazon SDE-3 — cost & operations first-class, work backwards from customer, decide and move; LPs Bias for Action and Learn and Be Curious)",
        "Section 11 Likely Interviewer Questions — all 7 domains, 12-18 Q&A, ending with the 🎙️ 60-second verbal summary"
      ],
      "toneAndLength": "TONE: First-person and collaborative whiteboard 'teachable senior peer' voice (Hello-Interview style) — 'Let's...', 'We'll...', 'Now we need to...', inviting the interviewer in. Incremental and anti-complexity: start small, explicitly resist early scaling ('Let me resist adding a cache here — we'll earn it in the deep dives'). Decisive but not dogmatic: state a choice plus its trade-off. Plain-English first, then the precise term. Numbers always rounded and say-out-loud-able. Heavily layered for SPEAKING ALOUD: every major section ends with a connected first-person 🎙️ Script (~3-6 sentences, contractions, no editing needed); short 💬 blockquote 'say THIS while you draw' lines throughout; 🗣️ plain-words / layman explanations for any jargon-heavy concept; emojis are part of the prescribed structure (🎬 🎙️ 💬 🗣️ 🧠 🤝 🆘 ⚠️ ⚡ 💥 🔀 ❓ 🗄️ ↔️ ↩️ ✅ 🔢 🔁). LATENCY CONSTRAINT: it runs in a LIVE interview, so the speakable opener (Sections 1-2: problem frame + 🎬 structure pitch, functional reqs, non-functional reqs, clarifying questions + assumptions) must stream FIRST as plain text with NO extended thinking and NO tool calls before it; deeper reasoning and tools are deferred to the Section 3 capacity math onward. LENGTH: long, comprehensive, single-pass — 11 full sections covering everything a senior interviewer might probe, but scripts kept tight (a spine to speak from, not a transcript). MULTI-TURN: after the first complete answer, follow-ups are answered directly and concisely; if asked to change/extend, re-output the full updated solution. CODE/PSEUDOCODE: this is HLD, so there is NO application/algorithm pseudocode in the answer body — code appears only in two narrow places: (1) realistic JSON request/response example blocks in the API section (Section 5), and (2) Python that the model itself writes to a file and RUNS via Bash to compute capacity numbers exactly (Section 3) — that Python is a verification/computation tool, with only its rounded results surfaced, never unrun code shown. Output is pure Markdown (tables with real line breaks, fenced code blocks with language tags, plain-text math, no LaTeX, no stray XML/tool tags)."
