{
  "summary": "Critically evaluate the HLD system_design_prompt.md for improvements — including whether clarifying questions should come BEFORE functional/non-functional requirements — via 4 independent reviewer lenses, then synthesize a prioritized recommendation.",
  "agentCount": 5,
  "logs": [],
  "result": {
    "orderingRecommendation": "HYBRID",
    "orderingRationale": "All 4 reviewers land on HYBRID, not pure clarify-first — so I push back on the prompt owner's \"clarify-first\" instinct as stated, while agreeing with its core grievance. The honest synthesis: the owner is RIGHT that the current order is wrong (a separate §2 Clarifying Questions sitting AFTER §1 Requirements is backwards and reads as committing-then-questioning), but a literal swap to \"§1 Clarifying Questions, §2 Requirements\" is also wrong and no reviewer recommends it. The decisive evidence cuts both ways: (a) you genuinely cannot write correct FUNCTIONAL requirements without first naming what the system does and locking the 2-4 forks that change the architecture (do we support group chat? is stock scarce?) — so a scoping pass must come first; but (b) Reviewer 4's empirical read of two real outputs (Flash Sale, Web Crawler) shows the §1-before-§2 order does NOT read badly in practice — the actual defect is CONTENT overlap (§2 re-asks quantities §1 already asserted as hard facts: \"thousands or a million?\" after §1 already assumed 1M), not sequence. And the canonical frameworks (Reviewer 3: Alex Xu Step 1 = \"establish design scope via clarifying questions first\"; Hello Interview = clarifying folded INTO requirements discovery) both REJECT clarifying-as-a-downstream-section but ALSO reject a cold interrogation. The senior signal (Reviewer 1) is decisiveness under clarification: ask the few forking questions as vetoes-able assumptions, then commit. The convergent fix is therefore neither swap nor keep — it is MERGE: a short scope-lock at the front of §1, functional requirements derived from it, NON-functional targets stated as provisional and gated on the forks, and the old §2 demoted to \"the forks behind my assumptions / what changes if I'm wrong\" with a hard no-duplication rule. This also fixes a self-contradiction the reviewers caught: §1 already declares \"Whatever you list here is EXACTLY what §6 builds,\" yet §2 admits a YES/NO answer can \"skip the whole reservation logic\" — i.e. §2 can invalidate the §1 commitment the prompt treats as locked.",
    "topRecommendations": [
      {
        "title": "Restructure §1+§2 into a scope-lock-first MERGE (the central ordering fix)",
        "why": "All 4 reviewers flag the §1-before-§2 order as the #1 issue. The current shape forces the candidate to commit functional requirements AND numeric NFR targets (99.99%, p99=200ms) before asking the questions that justify them, and §1's own 'this is EXACTLY what §6 builds' commitment is contradicted by §2's admission that an answer can delete entire flows. Empirically (Reviewer 4) §2 ends up re-asking quantities §1 already asserted, so it reads as retroactive justification, not scoping.",
        "concreteEdit": "Rename §1 to '## 1. Scope, Requirements & Assumptions'. Open it with a NEW 'Scope lock' micro-step: the 2-4 questions whose answer FORKS the architecture, each phrased as a vetoable assumption ('I'll assume reads dominate ~100:1 and single-region to start — stop me if not'), ending with a scope checkpoint ('here's what I'm treating as in/out of scope — add or cut before I commit?'). THEN functional requirements derived from those assumptions (show the link: 'since we assume scarce stock, the core flows are...'). THEN non-functional targets stated as PROVISIONAL bands tagged to the assumption they depend on ('p99 ~200ms ASSUMING single-region read'). Demote the old §2 to a short residual section reframed from 'questions you'd ask' to 'the forks behind my assumptions — what changes if I'm wrong', and add a HARD rule: 'Do NOT re-ask any quantity or constraint already asserted above; if §1 picked the branch, cut the question.' Update the <live_latency> opener ordering (lines 41-44) and <structure_pitch> to match: frame -> scope lock + assumptions -> functional -> provisional non-functional."
      },
      {
        "title": "Fix the broken session builder (hld_session_builder.md): stale path + contradictory mini-spec",
        "why": "Verified: the builder points at /Users/anshullkgarg/Desktop/projects/claude-gpt/ which DOES NOT EXIST (real files are under /Users/gbang/Downloads/algora/, where data/conversations/ confirmed exists). Worse, the builder embeds its OWN §1-§11 spec that contradicts the production prompt — it labels §4 'Data Model' (prod = Core Entities), §6 'High-Level Architecture' (prod = High-Level Design), §7 mandates a 3-part storage card (prod mandates 5-part), and the §8 tier structure diverges. An agent following the builder produces a structurally weaker, mislabeled artifact than the prompt specifies. This is a correctness bug, not a style nit.",
        "concreteEdit": "In hld_session_builder.md: replace all /Users/anshullkgarg/Desktop/projects/claude-gpt/ occurrences (lines 24-27, 143, 192-235, 242) with /Users/gbang/Downloads/algora/. DELETE the redundant §1-§11 mini-spec (lines 52-135) and the section-by-section duplications in the quality checklist (lines 263-279), replacing both with a single instruction: 'Section structure, headings, and per-section requirements are defined EXCLUSIVELY by system_design_prompt.md <output_format>; read that file and follow §1-§11 verbatim — do not paraphrase or re-derive them here.'"
      },
      {
        "title": "Cap and reframe clarifying questions: 2-4 architecture-forking only, no laundry list",
        "why": "Reviewer 1 (interview-realism) and the builder both push toward volume: §2's heavyweight 4-part template has no cap, and the builder literally says '6-10 questions per category'. A 10-question interrogation before drawing anything is the junior tell that loses points; a senior asks the few questions that fork the design and bundles the rest as stated assumptions. This compounds the ordering fix — capping is what makes the merged scope-lock fast and decisive.",
        "concreteEdit": "In the scope-lock step add: 'Ask ONLY the 2-4 questions whose answer CHANGES THE ARCHITECTURE — if a question does not fork the design, make it a one-line stated assumption instead, do not ask it. A long question list reads as junior; a senior states decisive assumptions and asks few sharp questions.' In the builder, delete '6-10 questions per category' and replace with the same 2-4-forking-questions cap so it stops contradicting the prompt."
      },
      {
        "title": "Add a global time/altitude budget so the opener does not become a multi-minute monologue",
        "why": "Reviewers 1 and 3 both flag length. The full opener now demands structure pitch + per-FR (feature + plain words + why-hard) + per-NFR (target + plain words + what-breaks) + 4-part clarifying block + gaps + multiple scripts — several minutes of talk before the first box is drawn, risking the 'breadth, no depth' red flag the prompt itself warns about. Reviewer 4 separately shows the headline number gets restated 6-8 times across sections, bloating output. Frameworks budget ~3-5 min for the whole opener and wrap-up.",
        "concreteEdit": "Add to <live_latency>: 'The entire opener (scope lock + requirements) should be ~3-4 minutes of talk — one short clause per plain-words/why-hard line, not a paragraph; aim to be sketching the high-level design by ~minute 5.' Add a de-duplication rule to <output_format>: 'State the headline number and the single core mechanism in FULL once (§3 and its deep dive); thereafter reference in <=6 words, never re-derive. Per-section scripts must add a NEW angle, not restate a prior section's number.' Add a framing note atop §9: 'Sections 9-11 are pull-not-push — surface the 2-3 items the interviewer probes; the rest is prepared backup, not a monologue.'"
      },
      {
        "title": "Add the missing senior/staff design concerns as first-class hooks",
        "why": "Reviewer 2 (distributed-systems architect) identifies a specific, namable set of gaps the otherwise-strong rigor invariants miss — each a standard SDE-3/staff probe: back-pressure/load-shedding (queues are unbounded today), rate-limiting/quotas (only 4 words in invariant 11, and its shared counter is exactly the coordinator invariant 9 prizes), observability/end-to-end tracing across the async hop, API versioning + cursor pagination (§5 has no hook despite the Microsoft lens calling for versioned APIs), and data lifecycle/TTL/archival (the largest table from invariant 3 grows unbounded with no answer to 'this is 50TB/mo — then what?').",
        "concreteEdit": "Add to rigor invariant 11 a back-pressure line ('for the hottest async path, state bounded-queue behavior block/drop/spill, the load-shedding order under overload — shed reads/non-critical writes first, protect the money path — and the trigger signal: queue depth / consumer lag / p99 breach'). Add §8 deep-dive coverage bullets for rate-limiting (algorithm + where limiter state lives + 429/Retry-After client contract, cross-ref invariant 9) and overload behavior. Add §9 observability sub-section (golden signals, burn-rate alert thresholds, and trace-id propagation through gateway->services->queue->worker). Add two §5 bullets: VERSIONING (state /v1 + additive-vs-breaking handling) and PAGINATION (cursor over offset + why). Add §7 PART D: DATA LIFECYCLE (retention window tied back to the §3 storage $ figure, partition-drop not row DELETE)."
      }
    ],
    "minorRecommendations": [
      "§3 capacity placement: it sits before §4 Core Entities / §5 API; neither canonical framework does this. Don't reorder — add a governing rule at §3's top: 'Compute ONLY the 1-2 numbers that flip a design decision now; defer the rest to the point in §6/§8 where a number drives a choice — no full capacity spreadsheet here' (Reviewer 3).",
      "Add a peak-to-average / burst multiplier to invariant 1/§3 ('always derive a PEAK number from average using a stated factor; provision and pick the binding bottleneck from PEAK, name the worst case — flash sale / regional failover'), and one row deriving connection budget via Little's Law (concurrency = QPS x latency_sec) vs the pool ceiling — §8 cites pool exhaustion but §3 never sizes it (Reviewer 2).",
      "Add CAP/PACELC framing to §10's consistency card + a one-line gloss in jargon_guard, so a candidate who did deep per-operation analysis can still answer the textbook 'are you CP or AP?' cleanly (Reviewer 2).",
      "Deepen idempotency invariant 7: state dedup-store TTL must exceed the longest client retry window (name the late-retry-re-executes race), size the dedup store from write-QPS x TTL, and require the async CONSUMER to be idempotent too (link to invariant 10's delivery guarantee) (Reviewer 2).",
