    "overallAssessment": "This prompt is already strong — well above most published rubrics. Its requirements framing, the 12 correct-by-construction rigor invariants (capacity derivation, idempotency, single-coordinator analysis, multi-region write topology, RPO/RTO, trade-off ledger), the Bad->Good->Great deep-dive escalation, and the speakable-script/jargon-guard scaffolding are genuine strengths that two reviewers explicitly called improvements over the canonical Hello Interview / Alex Xu frameworks. It does not need a rewrite. But it has one real structural defect and one real bug that warrant focused work, not polish. (1) The §1-Requirements-then-§2-Clarifying-Questions ordering is backwards — all four independent reviewers converged on this, and the prompt even contradicts itself (§1 'this is EXACTLY what §6 builds' vs §2 'an answer can skip the whole reservation logic'). The fix is a MERGE into a scope-lock-first §1, not the literal clarify-first swap the prompt owner is leaning toward, and not a do-nothing keep. (2) The session builder is materially broken: a stale, nonexistent path and an embedded mini-spec that mislabels and contradicts the production sections — verified, and it will silently degrade every generated artifact; fix it first since it's a 10-minute correctness win. Beyond those, the highest-value additions are a global time budget (the opener has crept into a multi-minute monologue) and a small, namable set of senior/staff gaps (back-pressure, rate-limiting, observability/tracing, pagination/versioning, data lifecycle). Net: keep ~90% as-is, fix the two structural problems, add the time discipline and the five gap hooks, and this is an exceptional interview-coach prompt."
